Abstract: Phase I & II of this study involved setting up and conducting a pilot survey of 40 U.S. training institutions involved in training AID-sponsored participants.  Through interviews with selected individuals at each training site, opinions and attitudes were elicited in the areas of:  a) participant selection, assignment, orientation, evaluation and personal needs; and b) training program administration, personnel, facilities and evaluation.  Specific recommendations based on the findings are presented in the study's Executive Report. (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: This Executive Summary describes the contractor's efforts:  1) to develop a procedure for collecting information, opinions and attitudes about the A.I.D. participant training program; 2) to conduct a pilot study of a heterogeneous sample of organizations involved in the program in order to determine the feasibility of a national study; and 3) to determine substantive results from the pilot study in order to provide A.I.D. with information and recommendations useful in improving the program. The contractor developed and pre-tested a questionnaire, trained interviewers, identified a sample of 41 organizations involved in participant training, and collected and analyzed data from 133 people interviewed.  Findings are organized into two major categories: participants (selection, assignment, preparation, expectations, orientation, training content and methods, and personal and social needs); and training organizations (relationships with A.I.D. and programming agencies, planning and executing programs, and evaluation). Many recommendations are presented in the report on virtually all aspects of participant training except for the post-training phase. (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: Loan to the Government of Tunisia to fund the construction of select water supply and irrigation projects.  A.I.D. funds will be used to: (1) construct a 2.8 million cu meter reservoir and related facilities, including a filtration plant, to increase the water supply for Tunis and suburbs; (2) expand the capacity of the Sbeitla-Sfax main water line to 3,600 gallons per minute and improve and extend the water distribution system in and around Sfax; and (3) install wells, an electrical distribution system, a pumping system, regulating basins, a water distributing system, and land development works necessary to provide irrigation for about 3,400 acres in the Cape Bon peninsula.

Abstract: In-depth analysis and case history up to 1/10/63 of 1954-initiated National Agric Dvlp Research Tech Assistance Project in Afghanistan. Proj designed to improve the quality/quantity of agric production & exportable crops through research programs, testing, & demonstrations. With assistance of Univ of Wyoming (UWy) contract and direct-hire technicians/advisors and an FAO technician, proj accomplishments thus far include six fully operational agronomic research stations; a model dairy and model poultry farm; over 100,000 fruit trees distributed & budded; annual distribution of 400,000 plants to farmers; development of high-yield varieties of cotton, sugar beets, and other crops; and testing of hundreds of varieties of agronomic crops.  Per acre production has increased seven times in certain cases and dvlp of rust-resistant wheat assures more uniform yields in this basic crop. Hampshire Red roosters introduced by the proj have become the dominant poultry breed. While proj exceeded original goals in some respects, it failed to reach many goals, hampered in large part by the Afghan Govt's incapacity in supply of personnel, land & funding resources.  Of particular consequence has been a failure to institutionalize proj outputs. Ministry of Agric (MOA) officials have not demonstrated sufficient interest in proj.  American technicians have superseded advisory roles to achieve proj results.  The number of Ministry officials assigned to proj has been reduced.  Of 12 BS partic trainees, only 2 remain directly associated with MOA component of proj.  USAID faulted for not insisting on joint coordination & planning. Proj results remain for most part unpublished. In marked contrast, full senior-level Afghan participation has helped shape steady progress & usable results in Helmand Valley Authority component of proj:  2 research stations are in operation and 2 partic trainees now head the agronomy & livestock programs. USAID has decided to phase out the UWy contract and retain a direct-hire staff equivalent to the number of Afghans assigned, making meaningful future progress dependent on Afghan commitment.

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training pogram was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  There are several specific recommendations in this report in the areas of pre-departure preparation, orientation, and follow-up.  (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: LOAN TO GOVERNMENT OF REPUBLIC OF MALI SUPPORTS COSTS FOR DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF THE HIGHER TEACHERS TRAINING COLLEGE (HTTC), A SECONDARY TEACHER TRAINING CENTER IN BAMAKO.  HTTC WILL BE COMPOSED OF (1) AN ACADEMIC BUILDING CONTAINING CLASSROOMS, LABORATORIES, AND ADMINISTRATIVE FACILITIES; (2) A LIBRARY BUILDING; (3)AN AUDITORIUM BUILDING; (4) A GUARD BUILDING; (5)A KITCHEN/DINING HALL; (6)DORMITORIES, CONSISTING OF MEN'S, WOMEN'S, AND GUEST COMPOUNDS, AND A COMMON LOUNGE AREA.

Abstract: This report, one 23 country studies conducted as part of a worldwide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in the Sudan since its inception in 1958.  The study was based on oral interviews with 100 returned participants, 40 supervisors, and 10 U.S. technicians; areas covered included the effectiveness of the training and suggestions for its improvement. Recommmendations are in the areas of orientation, support services, and utilization of training.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: Project to construct and equip the School of Law, Political Science, and Economics as part of a total development program for the University of Tunis.  The project's construction targets are based on an enrollment of 1,800 students in a four-year curriculum, but site planning for later expansion is included as well.  Specifically, the project will build five structures:  an administration-library building, two auditoria, and two classroom buildings.

Abstract: This report has been compiled pursuant to a Congressional request.  It includes all U.S. Government foreign loans with outstanding balances as of December 31, 1962, plus any loans authorized but not yet disbursed at that date.  It excludes fully repaid loans.  The majority of debts due the U.S. Government arose from the loans made by the Export-Import Bank, from the loans under Titles I and IV of Public Law 480 (Food for Peace) and from the loans made by the Agency for International Development (A.I.D.) and its predecessor agencies.  A separate section shows loans made by international organizations to which the United States has contributed, even though the total loans are from the commingled contributions of all members.  (Excerpt, modified)

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  The interview sample included 524 returned Korean participants, 305 supervisors, and 52 U.S. technicians.  The study contains an excellent set of recommendations which are principally in the areas of training design, location of training, selection, pre-departure preparation, English language, support services, follow-up, and utilization.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: FINANCES CONSTRUCTION, SURFACING AND/OR PAVING OF 86 KMS OF STATE HIGHWAYS IN PERNAMBUCO. HIGHWAY LINKS ARE VERY IMPORTANT. HIGHWAY PE-62 PROVIDES OUTFLOW TO PRODUCTION OF SIRIGI VALLEY, ONE OF MOST FERTILE IN REGION, AND LINKS IT WITH ITABAIANA, ZONE OF LARGE DAIRY PRODUCTION FURNISHING RECIFE. HIGHWAY PE-91 CONNECTS CARUARU, LARGE PRODUCER OF CEREALS, COTTON, MANUFACTURED PRODUCTS AND CATTLE HERDS WIH CATENDE, DEDICATED TO SINGLE CULTIVATION OF SUGAR CANE. PE-91 IS IMPORTANT BECAUSE SOUTHERN ZONE DOES NOT PRODUCE NEEDED COMMODITIES, AND MUST IMPORT THROUGH RECIFE, WHICH INCREASES ROUTING BY 235 KMS AND PRICE AND APPEARANCE OF MIDDLEMEN.

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of A.I.D.'s worldwide survey of participant training in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  The findings for the Ecuador study are based on structured oral interviews with 391 returned participants, 149 supervisors, and 31 U.S. technicians concerning the training program.  No recommendations are made per se, but several are suggested or implied in the areas of training design and support services.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a world-wide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in Greece from 1950 to 1962.  The report is based on interviews of 372 of 455 returned participants, 104 supervisors and seven U.S. technicians and consists of tabulations of interview data, with no analysis or recommendations. Abstract: EVALUATES PROGRESS IN DEVELOPMENT OF THE INDIAN INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY (IIT) AT KANPUR, INDIA AS OF 4/5/63. THE GOI HAS SECURED 1200 ACRES FOR A CAMPUS, AND 50 CLASSROOMS AND LABS, 100 STAFF QUARTERS, AND HOSTEL ROOMS FOR 300 STUDENTS HAVE BEEN BUILT. A DIRECTOR AND 24 STAFF MEMBERS HAVE BEEN WORKING FOR THREE YEARS. AN UNDERGRAD TEACHING PROGRAM BEGAN IN AUGUST 1960, WITH 100 FIRST YEAR STUDENTS HOUSED IN ANOTHER TECHNICAL INSTITUTE IN KANPUR. CLASSES OF SIMILAR SIZE WERE EXPECTED IN 1961 AND 1962. ABOUT 35 NEW TOP AND INTERMEDIATE INSTRUCTIONAL STAFF MEMBERS HAVE BEEN SELECTED RECENTLY IN ADDITION TO THOSE EMPLOYED EARLIER TO TEACH THE UNDERGRADS. MOST OF THEM HAVE HAD TRAINING IN THE US THOUGH NOT UNDER THIS PROJECT. NEW STAFF WILL BE JOINING IN THE NEXT FEW MONTHS TO START DEVELOPING POST-GRADUATE INSTRUCTION AND RESEARCH PROGRAMS. SOME DELAYS OCCURED IN SELECTION OF INSTRUCTIONAL AND RESEARCH PERSONNEL. DELAY WAS DUE TO NON-EXPANSION OF BUILDINGS TO START NEW CLASSES. PARTICIPANT SELECTION WAS DELAYED BY SLOW STAFF SELECTION. CEMENT SHORTAGES DUE TO THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY IN JANUARY 1963 SLOWED BUILDING CONSTRUCTION UNTIL MARCH 1963.

Abstract: AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTS EXPORT ACCOUNT FOR 90% OF ARGENTINA'S FOREIGN EXCHANGE BUT AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTION VOLUME DOES NOT MEET CURRENT SALE COMMITMENTS. THIS PROJECT SEEKS TO RESTORE A FLAGGING AGRICULTURAL SECTOR THROUGH INCREASING INVESTMENT, MECHANIZATION AND MODERNIZATION OF AGRICULTURAL SECTOR. AS PRODUCTIVITY INCREASES AND MARKETING OPPORTUNITIES EXPAND, STORAGE CAPACITY WILL INCREASE TO 9,574 GRAIN BULK STORAGE UNITS (TOTAL CAPACITY 6,025,000 TONS) OVER A TEN-YEAR SPAN IN 5 PROVINCES. THESE AND OTHER TECHNOLOGICAL CHANGES SEEK TO RESTORE BALANCE BETWEEN THE INDUSTRIAL AND AGRICULTURAL SECTORS AND RE-ESTABLISH ARGENTINA AS A MAJOR WORLD PRODUCER AND MARKETER OF GRAIN.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO THE COMPANHIA HIDRELETRICA DO VALE DO PARAIBA (CHEVAP) OF RIO DE JANEIRO, BRAZIL, TO ASSIST IN FINANCING THE CONSTRUCTION OF A 150 MEGAWATT THERMAL POWER PLANT WITH ASSOCIATED FACILITIES AT SANTA CRUZ, BRAZIL. LOAN WILL FINANCE IMPORTED US GOODS AND SERVICES REQUIRED FOR THE CONSTRUCTION OF TWO 75,000 KW REHEAT-CYCLE TURBINE /GENERATOR UNIT, TWO 507,000 POUNDS PER HOUR CAPACITY STEAM GENERATORS (1800 POUNDS PER SQUARE INCH GAUGE, 1000 F/1000 F, SUITABLE FOR FIRING OF BOTH BRAZILIAN COAL AND OIL), NECESSARY AUXILIARY STATION EQUIPMENT, A 132/33 - 13.8 KV STEP-UP SUBSTATION, AND 140 KMS OF 132 KV TRANSMISSION LINES. A 132 KV AND 33 KV TRANSMISSION SYSTEM WILL DISTRIBUTE THE POWER TO THE DISTRIBUTION SUBSTATIONS WHICH ARE EITHER EXISTING OR TO BE CONSTRUCTED BY PRIVATE, STATE, OR FEDERAL GOVERNMENT AGENCIES. THE POWER PLANT DESIGN WILL BE BASED ON THE UNIT SYSTEM CONCEPT. THE ARRANGEMENT WILL BE "SEMI-OUTDOOR" WHERE THE BOILERS WILL BE OUTDOOR UNITS WITH THE TURBINE GENERATOR UNITS AND MOST AUXILIARY EQUIPMENT HOUSED IN A POWER PLANT STRUCTURE. IT WILL BE IN THE DIRECT VICINITY OF THE PLANNED GUANABARA STEEL WORKS TO WHICH IT WILL DELIVER A LARGE BLOCK OF POWER, AND WITH WHICH IT WILL SHARE FUEL SUPPLY ACCESS FACILITIES. THE PRIME CONTRACTOR PROPOSED TO SUPPLY THE EQUIPMENT IS WESTINGHOUSE ENGINEERING INTERNATIONAL. AN INDEPENDENT US CONSULTING ENGINEERING FIRM, FINANCED UNDER THE LOAN, WILL ASSIST CHEVAP IN THE SUPERVISION AND EXECUTION OF THE ENTIRE PROJECT.

Abstract: Evaluates effectiveness of health services, 1958-1962, resulting from establishment of Haile Selassie I University Public Health College & Trng Center in 1954 in the Ethiopian provincial city of Gondar. "Elementary, direct, & indicative" evaluative methods appropriate to LDC's were used, including comparison of infant weights, incidence of intestinal parasites and scabies, and measurement of hemoglobin levels in school pupils and incidence of positive venereal disease in school pupils and pregnant mothers. Significant improvement, averaging 9.5%, in weights of Gondar infants was observed between 1958 & 1962, leading to the conclusion that the college's activities are effective.  No decrease was noted in the incidence of intestinal parasites despite treatment of infected pupils and education in hygiene and personal cleanliness.  A marked reduction in the incidence of scabies was observed, down from 70% to 12-15%. There was a drop in positive venereal disease tests of pregnant mothers (46% to 23.5%) and in school pupils (9% to 4.5%).  A significant improvement in hemoglobin levels was noted, explainable in all likelihood by the increased availability of food and modification of fasting habits. In summary, the data would seem to indicate that the individual mother now feeds her baby better, keeps it cleaner, and seeks more effective treatment.  The individual child keeps cleaner and has more and better food.  An outbreak of malaria in 1961 resulted in an increase in malaria incidence for the period observed; the evaluator hypothesizes, however, that malaria incidence should not be utilized for an evaluation of public health services.  No cases of variola minor were observed in Gondar between 1958 & 1962, probably due to regular smallpox vaccinations administered by the college.  General sanitation problems -- human waste contamination of food and elimination of vectors of disease, as in the case of intestinal parasites -- showed no significant improvement.  The evaluator concludes that the presence of the Public Health College & Trng Center is beginning to have an impact in area where no health services existed.

Abstract: This report provides descriptive data and insight into the participant training program in eight selected countries. While no specific recommendations are made, the report provides an interesting description of returned participants' views and attitudes about their U.S. training experience. Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a worldwide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in Thailand from 1951 to 1960.  Personal interviews were held with a sample of returned Thai participants, their immediate supervisors, and the U.S. technicians concerned with the projects under which training was sponsored.  Recommendations in the areas of training design, selection, pre-departure preparation, follow-up, and professional development are included. (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: The northeast is Brazil's oldest and most historic region.  The Portuguese explorer Pedro Alvares Cabral first discovered Brazil in 1500 near what Is today Salvador, Bahia.  Colonization of the area began in 1532 and it has been continuously occupied ever since.  Yet, remarkably little is known about the Northeast and statistical information is highly inadequate.  The purpose of this paper Is to present helpful background material and statistical annexes to introduce the reader to the land, the people the economy, its social problems,  Brazilian efforts to meet the problems of the Northeast (particularly through SUDENE,  the Superintendency for the Development of the Northeast) and the United states economic aid program in this area of Brazil.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: The purpose of this study was to examine past experiences in order to make future participant training programs pay greater dividends in the rapid development of economic growth in Taiwan. The study involved oral interviews with returned participants, supervisors, and U.S. technicians.  A series of recommendations are included on various aspects of the participant training program, some of which are too general and political to be of utility to planners and policy makers. However, there are specific suggestions in the areas of training design, selection, pre-departure preparation, English language, and follow-up. (Author abstract)

Abstract: To measure the adaptation of barley varieties, grain yields from 277 randomly selected varieties grown in repeated trials at three sites in South Australia were subjected to linear regression analysis using a logarithmic scale.  The mean yield of all varieties for each site and season provided a quantitative grading of the environments, and the analysis identified varieties specifically adapted to good and poor seasons, as well as those showing general adaptability. A two-dimensional plot (scatter diagram) was used, with mean yield and regression coefficient as coordinates for each variety. Although wide variation was evident in both mean yield and sensitivity to environment, the variation in sensitivity was proportionately less among varieties with higher mean yield, and the varieties with highest mean yield exhibited, within very narrow limits (regression coefficients close to 0.8), a similar degree of adaptation to all environments typical of the South Australian cereal belt.  Varieties from particular geographic regions of the world showed similar types of adaptation. The phenotypic stability and physiological and morphological characteristics of groups of varieties with specific or general adaptability are discussed in relation to plant introduction and breeding.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: This report, one of 23 conducted as part of a worldwide survey, presents statistical results of a study of A.I.D.'s participant training program in Costa Rica.  The study, which was based on completed interviews with 390 of 488 returnees (through June, 1960) and with 121 supervisors, aimed at determining whether Costa Rican participants were returning to the positions for which they were trained, were effectively utilizing their training, and were transmitting to others their newly acquired knowledge and skills.  The program was generally regarded as a success with some opportunities for improvement in all major phases, i.e., planning, implementation, and follow-up.  Specific suggestions are made for more participant involvement in planning and greater Mission and host country involvement during pre-departure preparation and post-training application of training.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a world-wide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in Brazil.  The study was based on oral interviews of 538 returned participants, 306 supervisors, and 48 U.S. technicians. Recommendations, which are general in nature, cover training design, location of training, selection, placement, pre-departure preparation, English language, support services, follow-up, and professional development. (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a world-wide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in Egypt 1952 and 1962.  The report was based on oral interviews of 309 of 445 returned Egyptian participants and 55 supervisors. Although no recommendations were made in this study, the findings suggest that the training period be extended (85% of programs were for less than one year) and that participants be followed up after return.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: This guide is to familiarize USOM Provincial Representatives with their job in Vietnam. Its contents have been taken from official publications and from speeches of Vietnamese and American officials. The guide is divided into seven chapters. The first six chapters provide information of a specific nature on the Counterinsurgency Program. Chapter Seven is a collection of significant reference information not included in other chapter headings. (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: PROJECT CONSTRUCTS, EQUIPS 2 LABS NEAR BUENOS AIRES. ANIMAL DISEASE LAB PROVIDES SPACE TO HANDLE FMD VIRUS STRAINS SAFELY, CONTRIBUTES TO CAMPAIGN TO ERADICATE FMD. PLAN IS TO REDUCE INCIDENCE OF DISEASE BY VACCINATION AND WHEN RATE IS EFFECTIVELY REDUCED, DISEASE IS ELIMINATED BY KILLING, BURYING INFECTED HERDS. CAMPAIGN EXPECTED TO TAKE 8-10 YRS AND CONTINUED RESEARCH THEREAFTER ON VACCINE, CONTROL METHODS INSURES AGAINST RESURGENCE. MEAT TECHNOLOGY LAB PROVIDES IMPROVEMENTS IN MEAT, MEAT BY-PRODUCT PROCESSING, MORE UNIFORM RESULTS, BETTER MARKETABILITY FROM APPLIED RESEARCH. DETERMINES IF FMD VIRUS IN COMMERCIALLY PREPARED MEAT CAN SPREAD DISEASE IN TO IMPORTING COUNTRY.

Abstract: PROJECT CREATES CENTRAL VETERINARY LABORATORY NEAR BAMAKO. CONSTRUCTS, EQUIPS 4 SEPARATE BUILDINGS: PRODUCTION, RESEARCH AND ADMINISTRATION, SERVICE ANNEX, MECHANICAL. LABORATORY PRODUCES VETERINARY VACCINES, ADMINISTERS MALI'S DOMESTIC ANIMAL INOCULATION PROGRAM AS WELL AS PARTICIPATION IN REGIONAL RINDERPEST ERADICATION PROGRAM. IT ALSO DIAGNOSES ANIMAL DISEASE AND EPIDEMIC CONDITIONS, RESEARCHES PREVENTION, CURE OF ANIMAL DISEASES, AND TRAINS SAFF FOR FIELD DUTY. PROJECT CONTINUED AS 625061000.
